p.strong: The Critical Sequence for Crash Safety

div.p: fsync is not about performance it's about CORRECTNESS. The OS caches writes in RAM. A power failure loses everything in RAM. Without fsync, your "committed" transaction might not survive a crash. The ordering rule:

blockquote.p: Journal MUST be on disk BEFORE any database page it protects is modified. This is the foundation of Write-Ahead Logging (WAL) protocols.

div.p: fsync is expensive (milliseconds), but data loss is catastrophic. The 1-5ms cost of fsync is the price of ACID durability.

ul.li: Journal: NOT on disk (in OS cache)
Recovery: IMPOSSIBLE! Original page data is LOST. Database is CORRUPTED.
